            <biogHist>
                <p>Ronald MacDonald was the son of Donald MacDonald, crofter, and Mary née Beaton.
                    He was born c. 1799, and married Catherine Campbell (born c. 1805), probably in
                    the early 1820s. In the 1841 census the couple are living in Smeircleit in the
                    south-western corner of South Uist with seven children: Marion (b. 1827),
                    Catherine or Kitty (b. 1829), John (b. 1831), Mary (b. 1831), another John (b.
                    1833), Donald (b. 1837), and another Marion, or Mary (b. 1839). Ten years later,
                    the family are still in Smeircleit, with the addition of James or Jamie (b.
                    1853) and Angus (b. 1857). By 1861 the family has moved slightly north to an
                    eight-acre holding in Geàrraidh na Mònadh, possibly as a result of the general
                    reorganisation of leases on the estate in 1856. In 1871 the family are joined by
                    Marion Mackinnon, an eight-year old grand-daughter. John has returned to the
                    house as a tailor, while Angus is working there as a shoemaker.</p>
                <p>Alexander Carmichael visited Ronald MacDonald inFebruary 1874. The latter appears
                    to have given Carmichael a song composed to one of the MacDonalds of Boisdale;
                    an anecote about Iain Òg Ìle while being ferried to Barra; antiquarian and
                    genealogical information, including material about his mother’s family the
                    Beatons; and a charm against bruising <span>Eòlas Pronnaidh</span>. Rather
                    uncharacteristically, Carmichael writes out a neater copy of the charm on the
                    following page of his field notebook, under the more distinctive, or indeed
                    archaic, title <span>Òra Cniogain</span>]. Ronald MacDonald’s wife Catherine
                    Campbell died some time in the early 1870s. Ronald MacDonald himself died barely
                    four months after his meeting with Carmichael, in June 1874. With no medical
                    attendant present, his death was ascribed to ‘natural decay’. His son James
                    signed the death certificate.</p>
